  <p>
    The Emerging Mind refers to Dan's idea that the mind is <i>an embodied and relational process that regulates
    a flow of energy and information.</i>
  </p>
  <p>
    It's a complex system that exhibits an emergent property: self organization. This organization (or order), takes place not
    only in your own <i>embodied brain</i>, but can catalyze mirror order in the <i>embodied brains</i> of others. It is <i>profoundly social</i>.
  </p>
  <hr>
  <p>
    Siegel's definition of the mind reminds me of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cellular_automaton">cellular automata</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    According to Stephen Wolfram, there's <a href="http://classes.yale.edu/fractals/CA/CAPatterns/Wolfram/Wolfram.html">4 types</a> of these abstract, computable systems.
  </p>
